Discussion from Feedback

In this section, we discuss the feedback we have received from our peers and the instructional team. Specifically, each piece of feedback is examined under different categories, and we explain how we have adopted these suggestions or why we chose not to.

Project Plans

  1. Comments: The second technical report specified the inclusion of the top K games (where 5 <= K <= 10), but the data visualization and table feature only included the top 10 games.

    Discussion: The description of this technical report indeed did not match our visualizations that were only about the top 10 games, which confused audiences. Therefore, we revised this technical report to specify that we were only going to use the top 10 games as the data.

  2. Comments: The third technical report needed some improvements, especially in explaining the reasons for choosing the types of the plot.

    Discussion: In this report, we had already indicated the reasons for choosing a scatter plot and heatmap, which was to showcase the correlation between discussion volume and sales.

  3. Comments: For the fourth technical proposal, it was kind of confusing whether this topic would use the time series ARIMA/ANN model or regression. If you chose the first model, it could also be used to make predictions.

    Discussion: This technical report included the types of methodologies that we planned to use, which were ARIMA or ANN. We ended up using only ARIMA in our ML milestone, which made this report confusing. Thus we removed the ANN model from this report.

  4. Comments: The idea for this business goal is great, but the manually labeled part may be hard to achieve, and as for the technical proposal part, there was another problem regarding the test part, it was also hard to get the classification accuracy if the data was unlabeled for the sixth business goal.

    Discussion: To achieve this goal, we came up with five categories: “bug report”, “gameplay discussion”, “story related discussion”, “lore discussion”, and “game items trading”. We then created a word list for each of these categories and if the post contained any of the words from the list, it would be labeled into one of the corresponding categories, which was not hard to achieve. Although the accuracy was low, we thought the reason for it was not the unlabeled data, but the scarcity in training features.

  5. Comments: There was some ambiguity regarding the method of obtaining these sentiment scores in the eighth technical report.

    Discussion: In this report, we did not mention the sentimental analysis model, which caused some ambiguities. Thus, in the revised version, we specified the model.

  6. Comments: The ninth business goal appeared somewhat ambiguous, lacking sufficient information and motivation.

    Discussion: This business goal was not clear in conveying its meaning. Also, we did not perform the NLP analysis for each game. Therefore, we plan to clarify and provide additional details in the revised report.

  7. Comments: It would be advantageous to include an examination of sales data during this chosen period in the final business goal.

    Discussion: Since the focus of this goal was about Esports games like DOTA2 and LOL, there was no sales data for these download-free games. Also, the external sales datasets did not cover these Esports games, making it unrealistic to examine the sales data.

  8. Comments: The presented 11th business goal from Milestone appears somehow ambiguous, lacking sufficient information and motivation.

    Discussion: For the purpose of clarify topic 11, we modified it by replacing “each game” to “top 10 games” as we analyzed in our project; so that this business goal will be more explicit for our readers.

EDA Work

  1. Comments: Lack or few uses of PySpark on data transformation and preprocessing.

    Discussion: Our data preprocessing processes for all the visualizations were performed using PySpark. Specifically, we read the Reddit submission parquet file, and then performed filtering and selecting relevant columns based on different visualizations. This section was in our EDA webpage with a detailed description.

  2. Comments: The barplot titled “Top 10 Best-Selling Games on Specific Platform” lacked clarity due to the absence of interactive elements like dropdowns to select platforms, which contradicted the title.

    Discussion: This plot showcased the top sales for games across different platforms. The title was confusing, and we changed it on our final EDA page.

NLP Work

  1. Comments: Sentiment by game type/event status should also include some percentages.

    Discussion: For the sentiments by game type and event status, we plotted a heatmap to show the correlation between these two topics. Therefore, it would have been unnecessary to incorporate percentages in the heatmap. In addition, Professor Anderson asked, “Do you want the reader to compare across columns or down a column?”. Since we were visualizing the correlation between sentiment and game type/event status, we compared it cell-wise instead of column-wise.

  2. Comments: Positive ratio/total subreddit plotly chart was mislabeled.

    Discussion: The y-axis label for the monthly based total subreddit post was mislabeled. We changed this label to the correct one.

  3. Comments: “Early September to September 22” what time period is this?

    Discussion: In the paragraph where we talked about the sentimental analysis of FIFA, we used the phrase “early September to September 22”, which was vague. Thus, we specified the year in this sentence to make it clearer.

  4. Comments: Can you unpack why Dota2 is more positive than LoL?

    Discussion: We visualized that Dota2 was more sentimentally positive than LOL, and we planned to search online in Reddit posts, trying to find the reasons for that.

ML Work

  1. Comments: What sort of comments are you seeing from those high influence users?

    Discussion: We planned to look through high influence Reddit users’ posts and search for frequent words, adding them in the ML section.

  2. Comments: You are almost entirely predicting a single class. What does that mean for your model performance? Is it based on random chance?

    Discussion: In the code notebook for our ML works, we performed a grid search of parameters and tried to find out which one was the best option by comparing the metrics for each model. We also had multiclass predictions such as predicting categories like “bug report”, “Lore Discussion”, etc.
